4. Extrapolation: How Many Species Are We Missing?4. Extrapolation: Wie viele Arten fehlen uns?

The species estimation problem: Even with 52,000 plots, we have not sampled every corner of Austria. Asymptotic estimators fit mathematical models to the accumulation curve and project where it would flatten completely (Colwell & Coddington 1994).

The Michaelis-Menten model is a classic asymptotic estimator borrowed from enzyme kinetics but widely used in ecology (Colwell & Coddington 1994):

\[S(n) = \frac{S_{max} \cdot n}{K_m + n}\]

where \(S_{max}\) is the estimated total species richness (the asymptote), \(n\) is the number of plots sampled, and \(K_m\) is the half-saturation constant (the number of plots needed to discover half of all species).

Das ArtenschÃ¤tzungsproblem: Selbst mit 52.000 Plots haben wir nicht jede Ecke Ã–sterreichs beprobt. Asymptotische SchÃ¤tzer passen mathematische Modelle an die Akkumulationskurve an und projizieren, wo sie vollstÃ¤ndig abflachen wÃ¼rde (Colwell & Coddington 1994).

Das Michaelis-Menten-Modell ist ein klassischer asymptotischer SchÃ¤tzer, der aus der Enzymkinetik entlehnt, aber in der Ã–kologie weit verbreitet ist (Colwell & Coddington 1994):

\[S(n) = \frac{S_{max} \cdot n}{K_m + n}\]

wobei \(S_{max}\) der geschÃ¤tzte Gesamtartenreichtum (die Asymptote) ist, \(n\) die Anzahl der beprobten Plots, und \(K_m\) die HalbsÃ¤ttigungskonstante (die Anzahl der Plots, die benÃ¶tigt wird, um die HÃ¤lfte aller Arten zu entdecken).

5. Spatial vs.Â Random: Does Geography Matter?5. RÃ¤umlich vs.Â ZufÃ¤llig: Ist Geografie wichtig?

The null model approach: To test whether spatial structure genuinely affects species accumulation, we compare two methods:

  • kNN (spatial): Visit plots in nearest-neighbor order â€” mimics how a field ecologist would walk across a landscape

\[{}^qD = \left(\sum_{i=1}^{S} p_i^q\right)^{1/(1-q)}\]

Not all beta diversity is the same. Baselga (2010) demonstrated that total beta diversity can be decomposed into two fundamentally different components:

  • Nestedness (\(\beta_{nes}\)): Species-poor sites are subsets of species-rich sites. Site A has species 1,2,3,4,5; Site B has species 1,2. This indicates differential species loss â€” some sites have lost species (or never acquired them) rather than hosting different species.

\[\beta_{Sorensen} = \beta_{Turnover} + \beta_{Nestedness}\]

12. Edge Effects: The Halo Problem12. Randeffekte: Das Halo-Problem

The boundary artifact:

When we study species accumulation in Austria, we face a methodological problem: Austria has borders, but species do not. A plot near the Austrian-German border may have its nearest-neighbor plot in Germany, not in Austria. If we restrict our analysis to Austrian plots only, the kNN algorithm is forced to â€œskip overâ€ the border, creating artificial jumps in the spatial walk and biasing the accumulation curve.

The halo approach solves this by including plots from neighboring countries (the â€œhalo zoneâ€) in the spatial walk but only counting species from Austrian plots when building the accumulation curve. This ensures smooth nearest-neighbor paths that cross borders naturally.

Why this matters: Edge effects can systematically bias biodiversity estimates. Plots near borders appear artificially species-rich or species-poor depending on whether cross-border diversity is captured or excluded (Colwell et al.Â 2004). For Austria â€” a country with 2,562 km of borders and complex geometry â€” this is particularly relevant.

13. Per-Site Metrics & Spatial Map13. Metriken pro Standort & RÃ¤umliche Karte

From curves to maps:

While accumulation curves summarize patterns across the landscape, we can also compute metrics for each individual site based on its role in the accumulation process:

  • Slope at 10 sites (slope_10): How rapidly is species richness increasing when 10 sites have been sampled starting from this point? High slope = the neighborhood is species-rich
  • Half-richness (half_richness): How many sites must be sampled (from this starting point) to reach 50% of total species? Low values = rapid accumulation = clustered diversity
  • AUC (Area Under Curve): A summary measure integrating the entire accumulation trajectory from a site

Mapping these metrics reveals spatial hotspots of biodiversity accumulation â€” areas where species turnover is highest and sampling efficiency is greatest (Colling et al.Â 2024).
